        content: "**Definition**: Arguing that one small step will inevitably lead to extreme consequences, without demonstrating the causal chain.\n\n**Example**\n'If we allow students to retake exams, soon they'll expect unlimited retakes, then grades will become meaningless, academic standards will collapse, and employers will stop trusting diplomas.'\n\n**Why It's a Fallacy**\nEach step in the 'slope' requires evidence. Without demonstrating why one step necessarily leads to the next, this is just speculation stacked on speculation.\n\n**How to Spot It**\nLook for chains of 'will lead to' or 'then' without evidence at each link. The further the prediction from the original action, the more skeptical you should be.\n\n**How to Call It Out**\n'My opponent assumes each step follows inevitably, but provides no evidence. Why would allowing one retake lead to unlimited retakes? They haven't shown that connection. Each step in their chain is an unsupported assumption.'\n\n**Important Distinction**\nSome slopes ARE slippery and backed by evidence. The fallacy occurs when the chain is assumed without proof. If you can demonstrate each causal link with evidence, it's a legitimate argument.",
