        title: "Appeal to Authority: Misusing Expertise",
        content: "**Definition**: Using an authority's opinion as proof, especially when they're not an expert in the relevant field or when their expertise is overstated.\n\n**Example**\n'Famous actor says vaccines are dangerous, so we should be concerned about vaccine safety.'\n\n**Why It's a Fallacy**\nExperts deserve deference in their field of expertise, but fame or expertise in one area doesn't transfer to others. An actor's opinion on vaccines carries no more weight than any other non-expert.\n\n**How to Spot It**\nAsk: 'Is this person actually an expert in THIS specific topic?' Being smart, famous, or expert in a different field doesn't qualify someone.\n\n**How to Call It Out**\n'My opponent cites [person], but they're not an expert in [relevant field]. Their expertise is in [different field]. We should listen to actual [relevant field] experts, who say [contradicting information].'\n\n**When Authority IS Valid**\nCiting relevant experts appropriately is not a fallacy. A climate scientist's opinion on climate change is worth more than a layperson's. The fallacy is misusing or overstating authority.",
