        content: "Identifying fallacies is only half the battle. You need to call them out effectively.\n\n**The Three-Step Response**\n1. **Name it**: 'This is a strawman fallacy'\n2. **Explain it**: 'They're attacking a distorted version of my argument'\n3. **Refocus**: 'What I actually said was... They need to respond to this'\n\n**Don't Be a Fallacy Robot**\nNaming every minor logical error can seem pedantic. Focus on fallacies that are central to your opponent's case.\n\n**Avoid the Fallacy Fallacy**\nJust because an argument contains a fallacy doesn't mean the conclusion is wrong. Address both the logical error AND engage with any valid points.\n\n**Tone Matters**\nCall out fallacies with confidence, not condescension. 'My opponent commits a strawman' sounds better than 'My opponent obviously doesn't understand logic.'\n\n**Combine with Substance**\nAfter calling out the fallacy, provide your substantive response. Don't rely solely on identifying the logical error.",
