        title: "Avoiding Fallacies in Your Own Arguments",
        content: "The best defense against fallacy accusations is not committing them in the first place.\n\n**Self-Check Questions**\n• Am I attacking the argument or the person?\n• Am I representing my opponent's position accurately?\n• Am I presenting false choices when more options exist?\n• Does each step in my causal chain have evidence?\n• Are my authorities actually experts in this field?\n\n**Common Pressure Points**\nFallacies often appear when:\n• You're running out of time\n• You don't have strong evidence for a claim\n• You're emotionally invested in a position\n• You're responding to something unexpected\n\n**Practice Honest Argumentation**\nThe debaters who commit fewest fallacies are those who prioritize understanding over winning. If you genuinely try to be intellectually honest, fallacies become less tempting.\n\n**Embrace Complexity**\nThe world is complicated. Arguments that seem too neat—too simple, too certain—often hide fallacious reasoning. Embrace nuance.",
